4174035936594, 0.014033524319529533, -0.0057145399041473866, 0.019893525168299675, -0.01564052328467369, 0.011664588004350662, 0.04089532420039177, -0.03111480362713337, 0.005887707695364952, -0.005842684302479029, -0.003198410617187619, 0.0019013832788914442, -0.007598606403917074, 0.012384966015815735, 0.011830829083919525, 0.005866927560418844, 0.0311979241669178, 0.023273762315511703, -0.020461516454815865, 0.010791822336614132, -0.013853429816663265, -0.0030061942525207996, -0.002613103250041604, 0.008159670047461987, 0.03745967522263527, 0.03862336277961731, -0.026058301329612732, 0.06439074128866196, 0.005995071958750486, 0.017012011259794235, -0.006001998670399189, 0.029175324365496635, 0.021154187619686127, 0.025171682238578796]], "input": ["\"TARGET REVENUE\":\"Target revenue is the projected total income that a company aims to achieve from sales of a product.\"", "\"PROPOSALS TO CLOSE COST GAP\":\"Proposals to close the cost gap include introducing 24-hour working in factories, incorporating quality assurance inspections, and increasing sales and marketing spend.\"", "\"EVALUATING THE FINANCIAL IMPACT OF SUNDAY TRADING FOR BITS AND PIECES RETAIL STORE\":\"Bits and Pieces (B&P) is considering opening for trading on Sundays to increase revenue. The case evaluates the financial impact, including additional revenue, costs, and potential supplier discounts.\"", "\"SUNDAY TRADING\":\"Sunday trading refers to the practice of opening a retail store for business on Sundays, which can lead to increased revenue and additional costs.\"", "\"SUPPLIER DISCOUNT\":\"Supplier discount is a reduction in the purchase price offered by a supplier when certain conditions, such as a minimum annual spend, are met.\"", "\"MANAGER'S BONUS\":\"Manager's bonus is an additional payment made to a manager based on the extra sales generated by Sunday trading.\"", "\"ENERGY COSTS\":\"Energy costs refer to the expenses incurred for energy consumption. In this context, it is calculated based on the total hours worked and the cost per hour. Additionally, energy costs encompass the expenses for lighting and heating the store during Sunday trading.\"", "\"STAFF COSTS\":\"STAFF COSTS\" refer to the wages and premiums paid to employees working on Sundays and the cost of hiring additional part-time employees. Staff cost growth is calculated as $91,000/$65,000, resulting in a +40% increase. In absolute terms, average staff costs were $16,250 in 20X0, calculated from a total of $65,000 divided by four employees. The additional staff cost amounted to $26,000, which is the difference between $91,000 and $65,000, covering the expenses for two additional people.", "\"SALES UNITS\":", "\"ADDITIONAL GROSS PROFIT FROM SUNDAY OPENING\":\"Additional gross profit from Sunday opening is calculated as follows: (16,000 per day (10,000 + 60%) * 50 days) = 800,000, Additional cost of sales (GP margin is 70%) = (240,000), Less additional supplier discounts (W2) = 57,000, Additional gross profit from Sunday opening = 617,000.\"", "\"ADDITIONAL SUPPLIER DISCOUNTS\":\"Additional supplier discounts are calculated as follows: Annual revenue without Sunday opening = 6 * 50 * 10,000 = $3,000,000, Annual purchases without Sunday opening = $900,000, Therefore, the company would not qualify for the discount. Annual purchases with Sunday opening (900,000 + 240,000) = $1,140,000, Over $1,000,000 so discount given on all purchases = 5% * $1,140,000 = $57,000.\"", "\"ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF THE MANAGER FOR SUNDAY TRADING\":\"The annual relevant cost of the manager for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: The salary is fixed, so the only additional cost of the manager working on Sunday is the bonus, being 1% of the additional revenue: (1% * ($10,000 + 60%) * 50 Sundays) = $8,000.\"", "\"ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF LIGHTING AND HEATING THE STORES FOR SUNDAY TRADING\":\"The annual relevant cost of lighting and heating the stores for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: Lighting (6 hours * $30 per hour * 50 days) = $9,000, Heating (8 hours * $45 per hour * 25 days) = $9,000, Total = $18,000.\"", "\"ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF RENT FOR SUNDAY TRADING\":\"The annual relevant cost of rent for Sunday trading is zero because it is not an incremental cost. Annual rent is not relevant because it does not increase (i.e. is not incremental).\"", "\"ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF THE LABOUR FOR SUNDAY TRADING\":\"The annual relevant cost of the labour for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: The relevant cost is the incremental cost: Premium paid to existing staff (2 * 30 * 50 weeks) = $3,000, Replacement staff on Saturday (2 * 20 * 50 weeks) = $2,000, Temporary staff for Sundays (2 * 30 * 50 weeks) = $3,000, Total = $8,000.\"", "\"ANALYSIS OF CEASING TUMBLE DRYER PRODUCTION AND PRICING STRATEGIES FOR STAY CLEAN\":\"Stay Clean manufactures and sells a small range of kitchen equipment, including a dishwasher (DW), a washing machine (WM), and a tumble dryer (TD). The TD has been generating negative contribution and is expected to become obsolete in a year. Stay Clean is deciding whether to cease TD production now or in 12 months when a new combined washing machine/dryer will be ready. The decision involves considering normal selling prices, annual sales volumes, total variable costs, potential loss of sales for other products, redundancy costs, and material cost savings.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}